00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:50.960
[Guest]: Listening to the most intelligent person on that topic speak

00:15:51.920 --> 00:15:54.320
[Guest]: So that's signal versus noise is sort of the other

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:58.240
[Guest]: major way people explain the issues online that

00:15:59.040 --> 00:16:00.720
[Guest]: you have

00:16:00.720 --> 00:16:03.520
[Guest]: Lots and lots of people talking not all of it is worthwhile

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:09.680
[Guest]: The question which then started bothering me is that how do you get the most useful information to come up?

00:16:09.680 --> 00:16:18.320
[Guest]: And sadly, it turns out that even a voting system like what slash.dot used where you could say that this comment is insightful

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:22.960
[Guest]: And this comment is funny or this comment is interesting did not necessarily make it such

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:27.280
[Guest]: That the most useful or relevant information came up most often

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.400
[Guest]: The most popular opinion still managed to be heard

00:16:31.120 --> 00:16:33.360
[Guest]: And this is generally going to be the theme

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:37.040
[Guest]: Of what we see with interactions online

00:16:37.040 --> 00:16:40.240
[Guest]: That it's just sheer numbers which tend to influence

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: how

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.640
[Guest]: We end up talking and what we end up talking about

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:48.980
[Amit Varma]: And like I remember I started my blog India Uncut in 2003-2004

00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:54.400
[Amit Varma]: And after a while, I found that my traffic was too much for me to have comments enabled

00:16:54.880 --> 00:17:00.720
[Amit Varma]: Because again, I couldn't handle the noise to signal ratio and I figured out rather than try and moderate or keep an eye on it

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:04.480
[Amit Varma]: Or whatever. I simply won't have comments because it's it is after all my style

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:06.480
[Amit Varma]: and

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:12.560
[Amit Varma]: You know save myself that mental bandwidth and I remember chatting with a friend of mine who ran a blog called Sepia Mutiny

00:17:13.120 --> 00:17:15.120
[Amit Varma]: a very fine blog

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:17.120
[Amit Varma]: you know desi americans and

00:17:17.200 --> 00:17:19.680
[Amit Varma]: One of the guys who started that was a chap called Manish Vedge

00:17:20.080 --> 00:17:23.040
[Amit Varma]: And Manish once told me when he spoke about his comments policy

00:17:23.040 --> 00:17:26.400
[Amit Varma]: And I was always very surprised because they had they also had very decent traffic

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:31.680
[Amit Varma]: But their comment section was always pretty good and he said oh we ban liberally and we don't just ban for trolling or abuse

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:38.640
[Amit Varma]: We ban for stupidity. Yes, which uh, you know brings an interesting question of even when you talk about signal and noise

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:43.520
[Amit Varma]: there are many categories of noise and there is a certain subjectivity to it and

00:17:44.080 --> 00:17:50.320
[Amit Varma]: The hard part for a moderator then becomes where do you draw the line? You don't want to you know

00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:53.600
[Amit Varma]: Have commenters or readers feeling that shit

00:17:53.600 --> 00:17:56.880
[Amit Varma]: This is only meant to be an echo chamber for people who agree with this guy

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:01.440
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time you do want to weed out bad behavior. And is it an issue sort of

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.040
[Amit Varma]: Finding those boundaries defining those boundaries have they changed over time?

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:09.520
[Guest]: So yes in general there is an issue quite often finding boundaries

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:13.360
[Guest]: Mostly because as you as you asked yes boundaries move

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:15.280
[Guest]: so

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:20.320
[Guest]: In general the way i've approached or what i've been exposed to has almost always been dominated by the uh,

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:24.080
[Guest]: General american viewpoint that free speech is critical and free speech is good

00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:30.240
[Guest]: And that the more free speech the better chances for drowning out bad ideas

00:18:31.280 --> 00:18:35.760
[Guest]: This was the general philosophy which which is why even on reddit. There's always been

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:38.960
[Guest]: Such a pushback against moderation where

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:45.280
[Guest]: Where what your friend did is turns out to be probably one of the only ways to deal with it and what you did

00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:51.760
[Guest]: Is turning out increasingly to be the only way for people to deal with conversations. There are many very large websites, which have entirely

00:18:52.320 --> 00:18:57.120
[Guest]: Shut down their comment section may be mistaken, but I believe either a scientific american or a major

00:18:57.840 --> 00:19:00.080
[Guest]: Website has shut down their comment section

00:19:00.800 --> 00:19:02.080
[Guest]: because

00:19:02.080 --> 00:19:04.320
[Guest]: It's a bit sad, but people don't interact

00:19:05.120 --> 00:19:07.120
[Guest]: In ways which are healthy

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:09.680
[Guest]: Or in the best spirit of humanity

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:15.760
[Guest]: So to go with an example of what happens when I ended up moderating on reddit

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:20.560
[Guest]: It was after the forum was actually dealing with such thing when the forum which was created was very small

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:25.760
[Guest]: And it was built on that principle that let everyone speak let everyone share ideas no matter how good bad or ugly

00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:28.320
[Guest]: And deal with the bad ideas

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:33.360
[Guest]: Unfortunately, it turns out that since your entire existence online is wrong

00:19:33.360 --> 00:19:37.040
[Guest]: Words are also very literally violence online. You can

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:44.240
[Guest]: Gang up on a person and prevent them from speaking. You can compress their ideas and you can move them away

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:52.160
[Guest]: You can form the internet really helps people find each other and this also means making lots and lots of ideological ghettos

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:57.200
[Guest]: So that process and those ghettos more are quite common in the internet

00:19:57.200 --> 00:20:05.120
[Guest]: What would happen on the forum is that if someone had an opposing viewpoint, they would get relentlessly hounded and since everyone was expected to behave on their own

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:07.360
[Guest]: In whatever manner was befitting them

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:12.400
[Guest]: Well, since no one was stopping them they behaved in any which way they liked which would quite often just be straight-up harassment

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:16.960
[Guest]: If you're a woman online, it's not a good scene. It's very very bad

00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:21.120
[Guest]: People would find them if by chance you let them in and you let them in and you let them in

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:27.440
[Guest]: If you're a woman online, it's not a good scene. It's very very bad. People would find them if by chance you let people know

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:32.400
[Guest]: You're a woman online then you would be targeted you would be targeted all throughout the web and you would be harassed

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:36.400
[Amit Varma]: What is sort of the men to women ratio in a place like Reddit for example?

00:20:37.360 --> 00:20:39.600
[Amit Varma]: In terms of active commenters, do you have any idea?

00:20:39.680 --> 00:20:43.760
[Amit Varma]: No idea because you'd imagine that it would become a sort of a vicious circle where

00:20:44.160 --> 00:20:48.800
[Amit Varma]: Women just don't feel welcome because there are so many men many of them abusive and therefore they just don't bother to

00:20:48.800 --> 00:20:52.380
[Guest]: Participate and I'm very certain that's the case and I'm sure

00:20:53.020 --> 00:20:57.260
[Guest]: Most people who go and interact out there either choose places where they are welcome

00:20:57.820 --> 00:21:02.860
[Guest]: Right, or they have a very thick skin or they just avoid they come to those places

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:06.940
[Guest]: where they know these conversations can happen and either try to engage or

00:21:07.740 --> 00:21:09.100
[Guest]: I'm or they

00:21:09.100 --> 00:21:12.220
[Guest]: Ignore those conversations focus on the parts which can be useful. But

00:21:12.860 --> 00:21:18.540
[Guest]: For the exact ratio. I don't know and knowing in itself would bother me because that would be mean that there's some way to

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:24.060
[Amit Varma]: Identify who's who yeah, exactly. Oh, so, you know, i'm not a reddit user per se once in a while

00:21:24.060 --> 00:21:27.260
[Amit Varma]: I'll see a link and go and I really like the keto subreddit which

00:21:28.140 --> 00:21:31.360
[Amit Varma]: Is a fantastic subreddit and i'm of course a keto evangelizer

00:21:32.700 --> 00:21:37.820
[Amit Varma]: So here's what it seems to me reddit's fundamental problem is let me just articulate this and tell me if i've got it

00:21:37.820 --> 00:21:41.100
[Amit Varma]: Right that on the one hand it is true that

00:21:41.820 --> 00:21:47.420
[Amit Varma]: Freedom of speech is something that really applies to a state acting against the citizens and if you are like a private

00:21:47.420 --> 00:21:51.180
[Amit Varma]: Party like a website you have the right to set whatever rules you want

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:56.620
[Amit Varma]: And if people don't abide by those rules, they can go elsewhere or you can ban them or moderate them

00:21:56.700 --> 00:21:59.340
[Amit Varma]: Anyway, you deem fit and therefore people shouldn't really complain

00:21:59.740 --> 00:22:04.860
[Amit Varma]: But the other way of looking at it is that community sites like reddit and facebook

00:22:05.340 --> 00:22:10.620
[Amit Varma]: Are so large and all-encompassing that for many people they are the world where they exist

00:22:11.100 --> 00:22:16.860
[Amit Varma]: And to stop somebody from expressing herself in a world like this would be very cruel

00:22:16.860 --> 00:22:21.740
[Amit Varma]: Among other things and the idea you mentioned of letting free speech prevail

00:22:21.820 --> 00:22:25.020
[Amit Varma]: I mean one of the fundamental defenses of free speech

00:22:25.580 --> 00:22:31.740
[Amit Varma]: Comes from the phrase a marketplace of ideas that to get to whatever the truth might be on any subject at all

00:22:32.060 --> 00:22:33.580
[Amit Varma]: You have to let

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:39.100
[Amit Varma]: All ideas find expression and then let whichever ideas win out in the marketplace of ideas

00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:43.740
[Amit Varma]: That's that's really the function but you can't stop anyone from speaking which is the original intention

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:48.700
[Amit Varma]: But uh, and that's reddit's dilemma that because of the noise to signal ratio

00:22:49.100 --> 00:22:53.340
[Amit Varma]: It must moderate but at the same time there are huge costs to

00:22:53.820 --> 00:22:57.900
[Amit Varma]: uh moderating both philosophically in terms of the principle of free speech

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:03.500
[Amit Varma]: And also practically in terms of what it can mean for users for whom reddit is a whole world

00:23:03.980 --> 00:23:05.980
[Guest]: Right, I agree. So

00:23:06.060 --> 00:23:08.060
[Guest]: funnily

00:23:09.100 --> 00:23:10.700
[Guest]: One part of the internet which did work

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:17.020
[Guest]: I used this idea recently and someone challenged it with a far more sophisticated, uh approach. They linked to an old

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:19.180
[Guest]: uh

00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:21.660
[Guest]: I think us supreme court or us court, uh,

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:28.140
[Guest]: or a law journal where they discuss this idea and the limitations on uh, how well the free speech the

00:23:28.860 --> 00:23:31.500
[Guest]: marketplace of ideas as an idea itself works

00:23:32.460 --> 00:23:33.340
[Guest]: and

00:23:33.340 --> 00:23:35.420
[Guest]: For one I like the analogy. It's very simple

00:23:35.420 --> 00:23:40.700
[Guest]: I like the marketplace of idea because it gets the idea across what we're really trying to do where we're trying to share ideas

00:23:40.700 --> 00:23:42.620
[Guest]: But there are a lot of things which are automatically limited

00:23:42.700 --> 00:23:48.380
[Guest]: So it's not that all speeches you're allowed to say fire shout fire or in a crowded. Uh,

00:23:49.100 --> 00:23:51.660
[Guest]: Theater, you're not we don't have unlimited free speech

00:23:51.740 --> 00:23:55.740
[Guest]: anyway, and if you're in india, there are a lot of topics which you cannot speak about because

00:23:56.380 --> 00:24:00.220
[Guest]: If you do and you talk about them in a certain way, you will cause harm to others

00:24:00.540 --> 00:24:02.540
[Guest]: And the state has decided that that's not okay

00:24:02.540 --> 00:24:07.260
[Guest]: Okay, in general there are certain ideas which we do not discuss in our marketplaces

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:08.780
[Amit Varma]: I think if I can just i've uh, you know

00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:12.060
[Amit Varma]: The shouted shouting uh fire in a crowded theater analogy is actually

00:24:12.380 --> 00:24:14.540
[Amit Varma]: One that I don't agree with and i've written a column about this

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:17.980
[Amit Varma]: In fact a couple of columns it's it bugs me a lot when people use it

00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:23.740
[Amit Varma]: Because here's the thing if you shout fire in a crowded theater if the patron does it when there's no fire

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:30.700
[Amit Varma]: He's defrauding his customers if a customer does it he is in a sense defrauding the patron and he's disrupting

00:24:30.700 --> 00:24:35.980
[Amit Varma]: Uh all the other people who have uh, you know paid for a good experience, which is being disrupted

00:24:36.220 --> 00:24:40.300
[Amit Varma]: So on all of these grounds you can condemn that behavior and stop it

00:24:40.540 --> 00:24:44.220
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to it's not an attack on free speech to do so per se

00:24:44.620 --> 00:24:49.580
[Amit Varma]: If someone shouts fire in a crowded theater, there are various grounds including property rights

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:54.140
[Amit Varma]: uh and contracts on which you can actually prosecute him and

00:24:54.140 --> 00:25:00.140
[Amit Varma]: Punish him. I mean i'm a i'm a free speech absolutist as you would have figured but I keep pointing out that we're going to have fun

00:25:00.140 --> 00:25:02.620
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but I keep pointing out that uh, you know

00:25:02.620 --> 00:25:07.580
[Amit Varma]: My my free speech absolutism really comes down to how the state deals with the citizens

00:25:08.060 --> 00:25:11.020
[Amit Varma]: Uh, because I believe the citizen should be in charge and not the state

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:14.780
[Amit Varma]: And people seem to have the opposite view as a default

00:25:15.340 --> 00:25:18.140
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't apply to how a private entity like reddit

00:25:18.460 --> 00:25:21.980
[Amit Varma]: Deals with its users because as far as I can see reddit has its terms of use

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:25.980
[Amit Varma]: And those terms of use obviously include things like you shall not do ad homonyms

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:28.460
[Amit Varma]: And you shall not abuse and you shall all of those things

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:34.460
[Amit Varma]: And they are entirely within their rights to kick out any users who have signed that terms of those terms of use and don't comply

00:25:34.860 --> 00:25:39.820
[Amit Varma]: So to me, that's not so much a free speech issue in the classical sense of the term

00:25:40.380 --> 00:25:47.020
[Guest]: So I too started out from the position of view that free speech is that my driving force has been to figure out what works

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:52.860
[Guest]: Figure out what works and i've come to the conclusion that if you if you use the analogy of the marketplace of ideas

00:25:53.020 --> 00:25:54.300
[Guest]: A lot of things don't work

00:25:54.300 --> 00:25:58.620
[Guest]: The big issue is that a lot of people can get together and suppress a good idea

00:25:58.700 --> 00:26:02.380
[Guest]: So a lot of people want to get together and they want to suppress discussion on

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:04.380
[Guest]: Uh racism, for example

00:26:04.380 --> 00:26:11.260
[Guest]: They want to suppress certain discussion on religion or they want to specifically focus discussion on xyz topic about a different religion

00:26:11.740 --> 00:26:14.380
[Guest]: and these things these the previous

00:26:14.380 --> 00:26:20.140
[Guest]: This protection and the shield which we had in the previous era was that these things were very amorphous. They were

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:22.620
[Guest]: not necessarily something you could

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:30.880
[Guest]: Tangibly see but as a moderator or as a user online these things happen every day now because all your interactions are about conversation

00:26:31.420 --> 00:26:38.460
[Guest]: You can end up spamming the feed you can keep or you can very subtly ensure that certain conversations get

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:43.280
[Guest]: Downvoted and disappear whereas other conversations which you prefer get or get upvoted

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:45.600
[Guest]: so it's now more a question of

00:26:46.240 --> 00:26:48.240
[Guest]: whether the original idea of

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:54.720
[Guest]: The original conception of this marketplace where everyone gets together and share ideas is still working and in the new era

00:26:54.720 --> 00:26:57.520
[Guest]: It's not practically speaking. There are many ways in which

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:00.240
[Guest]: Free speech as we knew it. It's

00:27:00.800 --> 00:27:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Done and dusted. I think you can argue though. I agree with you, but as a counter you could argue that

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:08.720
[Amit Varma]: The marketplace of ideas was always extremely slow to work

00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:14.800
[Amit Varma]: For example, if you had read it in say 1820 in America and someone said slavery is bad and we should abolish it

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:20.480
[Amit Varma]: the same thing would happen to them what you just described that the majority of people would just download them and

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:25.440
[Amit Varma]: Shout them out or troll them or whatever and it wouldn't matter and it would seem as if in the marketplace of ideas

00:27:25.680 --> 00:27:32.400
[Amit Varma]: Pro-slavery has won and then society sort of took its own time to change gradually. So it's never immediate

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:36.960
[Amit Varma]: But the whole idea I think of the marketplace of ideas is that at least those ideas are allowed to exist in some form

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:42.000
[Guest]: right, this is the marketplace of ideas if I remember correct that actually what you said is a sort of uh,

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:47.520
[Guest]: One of the criticisms of the original concept and said that there's never really been a functional marketplace in the first place

00:27:47.920 --> 00:27:54.240
[Guest]: Because there are several concepts which are as it is banned by the states or controlled by the states. You cannot discuss them libel

00:27:54.480 --> 00:27:58.480
[Guest]: So, um, there are certain topics which the majority will automatically take a stand on

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:00.960
[Amit Varma]: I think india is very harsh and unduly harsh on free speech

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:03.840
[Amit Varma]: But in the us the first amendment is really quite excellent

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:08.720
[Guest]: I think in terms it is and finally the the person who was criticizing the concept of

00:28:09.280 --> 00:28:12.000
[Guest]: free speech and the marketplace of ideas was a

00:28:12.800 --> 00:28:15.440
[Guest]: Person in on an american law journal, right?

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:17.840
[Guest]: So there are limitations

00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:22.160
[Guest]: No idea is perfect and you don't deal with platonic ideas in the first place and there will always be

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:25.520
[Guest]: the thing which was most critical to me to realize was

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.240
[Guest]: That when you started out putting rules in our forum, we said basic rules. Don't harass

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:32.000
[Guest]: don't

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:36.160
[Guest]: Hunt people and don't go and be abusive very simple straightforward rules

00:28:37.200 --> 00:28:40.240
[Guest]: And then what would happen is that once those rules?

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:42.720
[Guest]: got in place

00:28:42.720 --> 00:28:48.880
[Guest]: And people became familiar with them they go and we banned several users and said no you cannot behave this way

00:28:48.880 --> 00:28:54.580
[Guest]: You cannot just intentionally put insightful material. You cannot intentionally go and find this particular

00:28:55.120 --> 00:29:00.880
[Guest]: Uh subgroup of people you don't like for example furries and decide you want to just abuse them. That's just not okay

00:29:00.880 --> 00:29:05.280
[Guest]: There's no reason for you to use our forum to just harass furries

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:11.200
[Guest]: It's not something which we really care about and we're not going to give you a space to do that because that's

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:16.400
[Guest]: Goes and causes other problems. It makes other people upset and it just starts a chain reaction. Absolutely

00:29:16.560 --> 00:29:19.280
[Guest]: So that's one of the things where I agree with your friend that yes

00:29:19.360 --> 00:29:23.920
[Guest]: You need to you end up coming to a position where you have to use the ban hammer very often

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:26.160
[Guest]: and our first attempts were very

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:32.560
[Guest]: Distant and practical. We said we will generally use it and as little as we can and for the most egregious violations

00:29:32.560 --> 00:29:34.560
[Guest]: But what happens is when you move the frontier

00:29:35.200 --> 00:29:40.160
[Guest]: You have a new level of peace. You have no longer the same kind of horrendous things happening as before

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:42.720
[Guest]: But then what happens?

00:29:42.720 --> 00:29:45.600
[Guest]: People find new ways to abuse that they find

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:49.360
[Guest]: So the term which I love about this is fractal stupidity

00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:53.600
[Guest]: It once you've established a set of ground rules

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:58.560
[Guest]: They find that they can tweak these particular ground rules or they can find another way to harass someone

00:29:58.640 --> 00:30:03.280
[Guest]: They can just follow someone and constantly repeat certain things which are not offensive, but are

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:08.640
[Guest]: Either dog whistles or either just slanted the right way to read as offensive

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:14.160
[Guest]: Or they can constantly tag a user in a conversation. There are many ways in which give me an example of this

00:30:14.720 --> 00:30:16.720
[Guest]: all right, so

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:18.720
[Guest]: Once we've banned a lot of this behavior

00:30:18.720 --> 00:30:25.520
[Guest]: There were people who would find ways to show up in conversations about XYZ subgroup and say well

00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:30.080
[Guest]: These people have always done this what you expect and it wouldn't be outright offensive

00:30:30.080 --> 00:30:34.880
[Guest]: They wouldn't be saying these people need to die. They would always be saying something which was polite and

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:41.200
[Guest]: Obviously rude and now that was a problem for us because now they no longer we we were used to the old

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:46.400
[Guest]: Frontier, which was straight-up death threats hate speech abuse here. They're not saying anything wrong

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:50.640
[Guest]: They're using plain simple English and they're saying something which when translated is obviously offensive

00:30:51.040 --> 00:30:53.280
[Guest]: But we had restricted ourselves because of our previous rules

