00:45:36.420 --> 00:45:40.260
[Guest]: So one of the really cool things about subreddit one of its of reddit is subreddits

00:45:40.260 --> 00:45:42.280
[Guest]: And I think that's one of its great contributions

00:45:42.740 --> 00:45:46.440
[Guest]: To how we talk online so you can have a subreddit called r-pictures

00:45:46.820 --> 00:45:53.780
[Guest]: And r-pictures has a lot of people and they were sharing everything and a lot of people started sharing cat pictures or memes

00:45:54.500 --> 00:46:00.660
[Guest]: And those ended up dominating. So then what someone did is they created a separate subreddit for memes

00:46:01.700 --> 00:46:06.740
[Guest]: And that took off and then the people at r-pics said if you're putting a meme you can't put it here put it there

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:10.820
[Guest]: So that split the load and that's a really fascinating thing which made it very easy

00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:14.340
[Guest]: For these guys to do that before that you couldn't really do it as easily in a forum

00:46:14.420 --> 00:46:19.140
[Guest]: You didn't have you either went to a different forum to discuss cat pictures and a different forum to discuss memes

00:46:19.540 --> 00:46:23.860
[Guest]: Or you came to sub or came to reddit and then someone made a new subreddit to discuss

00:46:24.340 --> 00:46:29.940
[Guest]: This memes in general and you could go there you could go and just see all of those things and this actually happened

00:46:29.940 --> 00:46:36.580
[Guest]: So r-pics split up into other meme subreddits and those meme subreddits in turn split up into other subreddits

00:46:36.900 --> 00:46:40.740
[Guest]: There's from there. There's actually a subreddit just dedicated to the insanity wolf meme

00:46:42.340 --> 00:46:46.820
[Guest]: And there's another really interesting feature which used to be allowed initially which was when

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:49.700
[Guest]: People were not very happy with the moderators

00:46:50.100 --> 00:46:53.780
[Guest]: They could just make another subreddit and then move en masse there

00:46:54.020 --> 00:46:57.800
[Guest]: So this happened if I remember correctly it happened very famously to r-marijuana

00:46:57.800 --> 00:47:04.200
[Guest]: So for some reason the moderator out there had some issues and the team and the users who were going there weren't too happy

00:47:04.680 --> 00:47:07.180
[Guest]: So they moved en masse to r-trees

00:47:08.920 --> 00:47:12.200
[Guest]: Which is why anytime you go to r-trees, it's not about plants

00:47:12.840 --> 00:47:14.840
[Guest]: It's about a very specific type of herb

00:47:15.160 --> 00:47:19.400
[Guest]: So what happened to the tree lovers? They moved to r-marijuana later on if I remember correctly

00:47:20.200 --> 00:47:22.200
[Guest]: As I recall, I think that's what happened

00:47:22.280 --> 00:47:23.640
[Amit Varma]: Right. So for a newcomer to reddit

00:47:23.640 --> 00:47:28.200
[Guest]: This is all very confusing that you love trees and you want to go to r-marijuana. Yes, it is very much so

00:47:28.680 --> 00:47:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Right, but isn't this also like on the one hand?

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:33.480
[Amit Varma]: This is very benign and very useful in the sense that okay

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:36.600
[Amit Varma]: You go from pics to memes and from memes to eternal wolf or whatever

00:47:37.160 --> 00:47:41.340
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand it can also sort of drive people to ideological silos

00:47:41.640 --> 00:47:44.440
[Guest]: Which is something that's kind of happened in the broader internet. Exactly

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:48.840
[Guest]: And so all of this possible even the movement of people to r-trees

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:52.120
[Guest]: Happened because we did not have a lot of moderating tools at that time

00:47:52.120 --> 00:47:57.960
[Guest]: Right. So this is an example of one of the tensions which occurs for the need to be able to moderate and stop people talking

00:47:58.040 --> 00:48:03.720
[Guest]: About or harming each other online and the freedom to expand into other things. Not all things are benign

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:06.700
[Guest]: I am generally in favor of moderating tools out of necessity

00:48:06.920 --> 00:48:11.560
[Guest]: So one of the tools which we ended up which people not we but moderators in general ended up creating

00:48:11.880 --> 00:48:15.880
[Guest]: Is a tool which helps them go through all the comments which are posted on a forum

00:48:16.040 --> 00:48:21.080
[Guest]: There's a feed where you can see the newest comment and it would check for very specific keywords for example

00:48:21.080 --> 00:48:25.320
[Guest]: Well niggers or other words, which would be very clear-cut

00:48:25.880 --> 00:48:30.840
[Guest]: Attempts at hate speech so that way you would be flagged immediately that okay someone out here in your forum

00:48:30.840 --> 00:48:32.840
[Guest]: So you only look at what's flagged?

00:48:32.840 --> 00:48:36.440
[Guest]: Initially, we would try to look at on we would participate in a lot of things

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:38.840
[Guest]: But at a certain point of time we just had to just look at the queue

00:48:39.400 --> 00:48:42.840
[Guest]: You have to look at what's flagged either by users or based on watch lists

00:48:43.480 --> 00:48:48.120
[Guest]: For obvious keywords like i'm going to kill you or die and so on so forth

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:52.520
[Guest]: And of course racial slurs and so on and other similar words. So

00:48:53.160 --> 00:48:54.600
[Guest]: It's always

00:48:54.600 --> 00:49:00.440
[Guest]: About looking at that queue and quite often a lot of forums don't even have enough moderators to manage that

00:49:00.920 --> 00:49:04.440
[Guest]: If it's a topic constrained forum where generally people aren't going to be talking about

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:10.780
[Guest]: Incendiary topics you should usually be able to manage the workload the higher the barrier to entry in that conversation

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:14.760
[Guest]: Usually the better the conversation because to get in

00:49:14.760 --> 00:49:17.720
[Guest]: It's not that easy. You have to know what if you're going to talk about

00:49:18.440 --> 00:49:19.880
[Guest]: um

00:49:19.880 --> 00:49:22.040
[Guest]: Let's say a very complex game

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:28.040
[Guest]: For example, the only people who can play that game are people who've passed the barrier have the time and willingness to indulge themselves

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:33.000
[Guest]: In a certain level of effort everyone else out there is also spending the same amount of effort

00:49:33.160 --> 00:49:37.000
[Guest]: So it's very easy to make out a faker or a poser or someone who's just talking about it

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:41.640
[Guest]: But doesn't know what he's talking about. So the conversation out there tends to be on topic and very neat

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:44.040
[Guest]: And that has a very nice sense of community

00:49:44.120 --> 00:49:48.360
[Guest]: The other subreddits which tend to work out are ones which have very heavy moderation like ask history

00:49:48.680 --> 00:49:55.880
[Guest]: Ask history has a dedicated team of volunteer people with backgrounds in specific parts of history and they are

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:01.000
[Guest]: Educators teachers master holders and phd holders on those topics

00:50:01.240 --> 00:50:05.960
[Guest]: So any time of any question that is asked and only as far as I remember only questions can be asked

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:12.120
[Guest]: Can be asked the first response has to be a qualified and informed response with sourcing

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:15.400
[Guest]: So you can ask whatever question and you will usually get a good answer

00:50:15.960 --> 00:50:18.840
[Guest]: If you go in there to just make jokes about oh, you know

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:21.960
[Guest]: Well, the pyramids were made by aliens comments like that disappear

00:50:22.360 --> 00:50:26.040
[Guest]: They immediately removed and the only thing which remains is high quality conversation

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:29.480
[Amit Varma]: So in the sense they are also doing what my friend Manish used to do at sepia mutiny

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:34.440
[Amit Varma]: They're banning for stupidity that particular subreddit. Yes, or to be put a finer point on it

00:50:34.440 --> 00:50:36.440
[Guest]: They're banning noise

00:50:36.520 --> 00:50:41.320
[Guest]: They have a very clear-cut definition of signal and there's a very easy way to say this is signal

00:50:41.640 --> 00:50:46.120
[Guest]: Because it's a very limited topic generally when you have a limited topic, you can do a good job

00:50:46.120 --> 00:50:51.400
[Guest]: For example, you're talking about music and you're talking about a specific type of music or how to play a specific instrument

00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:57.160
[Guest]: That would usually work a lot better unless you suddenly got into a war about which musician you like over the other

00:50:57.560 --> 00:51:03.480
[Guest]: Those are different but even there the moderators can step in and say we're not going to really have a fight on these topics

00:51:03.480 --> 00:51:05.160
[Guest]: You can move it to someplace else

00:51:05.160 --> 00:51:09.960
[Amit Varma]: so it seems to me that one of the real problems with the moving away from reddit for just a moment because the question

00:51:09.960 --> 00:51:11.720
[Amit Varma]: occurred to me is that

00:51:11.720 --> 00:51:15.480
[Amit Varma]: Uh, this becomes a problem at scale when you don't have specific subjects

00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:16.680
[Amit Varma]: For example with facebook

00:51:16.680 --> 00:51:22.520
[Amit Varma]: I imagine how the moderation is that everyone who flags something that goes into some kind of queue and they have like

00:51:22.920 --> 00:51:28.520
[Amit Varma]: Uh, they have some call center somewhere where they have thousand two thousand people just sitting at comms and one after the other these images

00:51:28.520 --> 00:51:31.080
[Amit Varma]: Flash up and they're all general. They're not specific

00:51:31.080 --> 00:51:34.440
[Amit Varma]: So it's not like a knowledge-based thing like ask history where the guidelines are clear

00:51:34.760 --> 00:51:39.580
[Amit Varma]: You ban this you don't ban that and they have to make subjective calls based on general guidelines

00:51:39.880 --> 00:51:44.360
[Amit Varma]: And there is often very little recourse available because if they if they delete something they delete something

00:51:44.680 --> 00:51:46.840
[Amit Varma]: How does that work and what are the ways around that?

00:51:47.560 --> 00:51:48.280
[Guest]: so

00:51:48.280 --> 00:51:53.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I completely agree with you where the more subjective it is the more difficult it is and when we're talking about subjective at facebook

00:51:53.160 --> 00:51:59.880
[Guest]: Scale we're talking about what's subjective in one part of india and what's no subjective in america and india and america alone have very different

00:51:59.880 --> 00:52:07.480
[Guest]: Concepts legally about what is free and what is fair what is okay speech like the term chinky eyes would be interpreted differently

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:10.840
[Amit Varma]: By someone here and someone in minnesota, for example, so, you know

00:52:11.080 --> 00:52:15.320
[Guest]: yeah, and out and what you tend to see is that there's a sort of cross-pollination that

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:20.520
[Guest]: All of those that if you're using any of those words we you tend to say, okay, maybe that person's racist

00:52:20.840 --> 00:52:22.840
[Guest]: It may not be it it is

00:52:22.920 --> 00:52:26.360
[Guest]: Quite often and now it's the de jure to assume that's racist, right?

00:52:26.360 --> 00:52:30.840
[Guest]: So while back in the day, maybe it was not now it is so there's also a sort of

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:36.600
[Guest]: Effect where people are learning what cultural norms exist in other places

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:44.120
[Guest]: And online is sort of being transplanted also to other nations in other countries sometimes for the better sometimes just

00:52:44.920 --> 00:52:48.440
[Amit Varma]: It's an alien entrant because what i'd imagine is from what you describe of reddit

00:52:48.680 --> 00:52:54.920
[Amit Varma]: Is that the way the moderators work on different subreddits and so on is something that's evolved over a period of many many years

00:52:54.920 --> 00:52:59.400
[Guest]: Very much learning and discussion and tool and tool creation. We did not like so

00:52:59.800 --> 00:53:06.040
[Guest]: Basically people end up blocking mentions of certain subreddits. So if that old moderator on uh,

00:53:06.440 --> 00:53:11.400
[Guest]: That particular subreddit or marijuana had these tools. He could basically block all mention of our trees

00:53:11.640 --> 00:53:13.640
[Guest]: So no one would know it would exist. Wow

00:53:14.120 --> 00:53:18.680
[Guest]: So it would be it would have to be done through various roundabout methods. It would be much harder

00:53:18.680 --> 00:53:21.640
[Guest]: So it's not it's a lot harder for people to move with their feet

00:53:21.640 --> 00:53:27.480
[Guest]: And this is an example of where there's a tension between the creation of tools to make it easier for people to deal with

00:53:28.440 --> 00:53:30.040
[Guest]: basically assholes

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:32.040
[Guest]: And how those tools end up

00:53:32.580 --> 00:53:35.800
[Guest]: Inadvertently stopping expansion into other spaces and here's the thing

00:53:35.880 --> 00:53:41.000
[Amit Varma]: It's this is something that's evolved over a period of time into a kind of science at reddit where you have all these years

00:53:41.080 --> 00:53:46.680
[Amit Varma]: Of collective experience and you've reached certain ways of working in certain norms in the moderating community at reddit

00:53:46.680 --> 00:53:52.520
[Amit Varma]: But what companies like facebook and twitter and so on are having to do is just to set rules on the fly and just deal

00:53:52.520 --> 00:53:54.040
[Amit Varma]: with shit on the fly without

00:53:54.040 --> 00:53:56.360
[Amit Varma]: You know having these years and years of processes

00:53:57.080 --> 00:54:00.280
[Guest]: I would say that making shit up on the fly is basically the rule

00:54:00.680 --> 00:54:03.480
[Guest]: It's if you have the time you go read up on

00:54:03.960 --> 00:54:08.440
[Guest]: The rules of what free speech are or like what some court cases you go and educate yourself

00:54:08.680 --> 00:54:14.120
[Guest]: But in general everyone's making this shit up on the fly and at the end of the day, I think what's deciding it is

00:54:14.680 --> 00:54:16.120
[Guest]: What works?

00:54:16.120 --> 00:54:19.160
[Guest]: So for a lot of people it just they can't manage conversations

00:54:19.160 --> 00:54:26.120
[Guest]: They just remove it for a lot of other people. It's just constant banning and removal of conversations which do not match

00:54:26.600 --> 00:54:34.360
[Guest]: The stated purpose of the forum which results in what you'd mentioned silos. So for example, there's a very large forum dedicated to

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:39.480
[Guest]: uh, the current sitting president of the united states of america with the donald and

00:54:39.960 --> 00:54:42.840
[Guest]: for a very long time they figured out ways in which

00:54:42.840 --> 00:54:46.600
[Guest]: They could make sure that their topics showed up on the front page

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:50.760
[Guest]: So that everyone else on the forum had to watch it and they were quite pleased with being able to do that

00:54:51.320 --> 00:54:58.040
[Guest]: Eventually reddit changed the entire way the front page algorithm worked to prevent users from ganging together and gaming the front page

00:54:58.680 --> 00:55:03.000
[Guest]: So one of the issues over here is that the donald which is the name of the subreddit

00:55:03.720 --> 00:55:07.080
[Guest]: Over there. They if you are critical of the president they remove you

00:55:07.080 --> 00:55:14.040
[Guest]: Conversely other subreddits now notice if you have posted in the donald and then they remove you for just interacting in that space

00:55:14.040 --> 00:55:16.040
[Guest]: So even if it is a question

00:55:16.120 --> 00:55:21.080
[Guest]: Innocuously stated that you know, why is he doing this? You will find yourself banned from several other subreddits

00:55:21.080 --> 00:55:23.480
[Guest]: They will just say you are not allowed to speak here

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:26.680
[Guest]: It's a very strange evolution of

00:55:27.560 --> 00:55:31.960
[Guest]: Group warfare which has occurred because of this this echo chamber effect

00:55:31.960 --> 00:55:34.600
[Guest]: I don't even know how to explain or understand this particular

00:55:34.600 --> 00:55:39.720
[Amit Varma]: So the the social scientist cast sunstein a kind of term group polarization

00:55:40.040 --> 00:55:44.440
[Amit Varma]: And what they did was I think he and his colleagues did a study where they got a bunch of

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:46.520
[Amit Varma]: republicans and

00:55:46.520 --> 00:55:50.200
[Amit Varma]: Democrats kind of together and they took their positions on a variety of issues

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:55.320
[Amit Varma]: And then they put them together in with like-minded people and they also put them together in mixed groups

00:55:55.640 --> 00:55:57.640
[Amit Varma]: And they found that those who were

00:55:58.200 --> 00:56:02.280
[Amit Varma]: Huddled together with like-minded people all of them tended to grow more

00:56:02.280 --> 00:56:05.640
[Amit Varma]: All of them tended to grow more extreme in their opinion

00:56:06.680 --> 00:56:08.040
[Amit Varma]: you know

00:56:08.040 --> 00:56:10.680
[Amit Varma]: Than the other groups and what this did was that it?

00:56:11.880 --> 00:56:17.320
[Amit Varma]: And when we form echo chambers, we essentially then interact only with like-minded people whose ideas already match us

00:56:17.640 --> 00:56:25.320
[Amit Varma]: The confirmation bias kicks in where we ignore all ideas from outside and we only take in the news that conforms to our biases

00:56:25.880 --> 00:56:27.080
[Amit Varma]: and

00:56:27.080 --> 00:56:30.040
[Amit Varma]: These groups get further and further apart. And finally you find that

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:35.640
[Amit Varma]: Uh in society, we are not talking to each other anymore. We are talking past each other. We are abusing each other

00:56:35.960 --> 00:56:38.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean one of my constant complaints is that

00:56:39.720 --> 00:56:42.920
[Amit Varma]: Why political discourse is pretty much finished on social media

00:56:42.920 --> 00:56:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Especially twitter is that all argument comes down to attacking the person and not the argument

00:56:49.240 --> 00:56:55.400
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand and on the other hand virtue signaling to raise your status within your own in group

00:56:55.800 --> 00:56:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Rather than honestly trying to engage with the other side, right?

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.480
[Guest]: So it's a lot of just throwing headlines at each other

00:57:01.720 --> 00:57:04.840
[Guest]: You're not really talking to the other person you want to show to the rest of your team

00:57:05.160 --> 00:57:09.640
[Guest]: Look that guy's an idiot. I am so great. I've made him shut up. That's generally the point

00:57:09.880 --> 00:57:14.120
[Guest]: it's so the echo chamber effect is very insidious and this is something which

00:57:14.680 --> 00:57:20.620
[Guest]: Again, this is about the frontier constantly moving as we improve on our tools and improve on our ways to deal with communication

00:57:20.920 --> 00:57:23.080
[Guest]: We find new and new effects which we didn't intend

00:57:23.080 --> 00:57:28.620
[Guest]: So reddit had a really simple way back then you could just upvote a topic and you would see lots of interesting conversations

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:32.440
[Guest]: And now because so many people ended up using that for their own gain

00:57:32.760 --> 00:57:37.560
[Guest]: So they would create they would try to spam or they would try to control conversations or they would just try to

00:57:37.960 --> 00:57:41.960
[Guest]: Be power users or just be the most the one to make the funniest comment

00:57:42.520 --> 00:57:46.120
[Guest]: There were constant rules and changes to the way the algorithm works to make it more complex

00:57:47.400 --> 00:57:49.160
[Guest]: While that has had positive benefits

00:57:49.160 --> 00:57:54.360
[Guest]: One of the side effects is that now it's just enhanced the echo chamber effect you tend to go to your group

00:57:54.680 --> 00:58:00.280
[Guest]: And then in your group you only argue about the things which you have already decided and anytime someone else says something different

00:58:00.920 --> 00:58:04.200
[Guest]: That person is immediately chucked out. It's it's really

00:58:05.320 --> 00:58:07.660
[Guest]: It's really creating a very disheartening situation

00:58:08.200 --> 00:58:14.380
[Amit Varma]: And would you say that this is not something necessarily brought about by the internet or by technology, but this is a human characteristic

00:58:14.380 --> 00:58:20.540
[Amit Varma]: characteristic that is amplified by technology like technology amplifies both the best and the worst and

00:58:20.860 --> 00:58:27.600
[Amit Varma]: It enables both our best and worst instincts and this tendency to think tribalistically and to form these sort of silos

00:58:27.980 --> 00:58:31.680
[Amit Varma]: Is something that is inherent but that is now being enabled by technology

00:58:32.300 --> 00:58:34.300
[Amit Varma]: and therefore it becomes

00:58:36.040 --> 00:58:42.300
[Amit Varma]: Problematic and complex to give it a moral dimension and to say that no things should not be like this. So I think I

00:58:42.300 --> 00:58:48.240
[Guest]: I don't remember the full argument. My personal gut take is that this is because of technology

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:50.780
[Guest]: that inherently

00:58:50.780 --> 00:58:53.580
[Guest]: This is a new way for human beings to be with each other

00:58:54.300 --> 00:58:57.420
[Guest]: And the problems it causes are inherently because of the medium

00:58:57.980 --> 00:59:04.460
[Guest]: So I think this is a much faster cycle. You get your comments you get your responses a lot quicker and it's also

00:59:04.940 --> 00:59:06.220
[Guest]: very context poor

00:59:06.220 --> 00:59:10.700
[Guest]: So like when i'm talking to you guys and I can see all of you all I can see whether you're interested bored tired cold

00:59:10.700 --> 00:59:13.100
[Guest]: It gives me a lot of information on what your state of mind is

00:59:13.660 --> 00:59:17.340
[Guest]: But if i'm and by making eye contact I can also figure out I can also

00:59:17.820 --> 00:59:19.900
[Guest]: Understand your body language. You can understand mine

00:59:19.900 --> 00:59:24.220
[Guest]: You can show so many things our brains are really well designed for dealing with other people

00:59:24.700 --> 00:59:27.740
[Guest]: Our music our dance our entire culture is about that but online

00:59:28.620 --> 00:59:33.180
[Guest]: You just see what's written. You don't know the tone. You don't know the background

00:59:33.260 --> 00:59:37.100
[Guest]: You don't know whether the person is a angry person sad person and he's had a bad day

00:59:37.100 --> 00:59:41.100
[Guest]: Whether someone has beat him up or not. You don't know any of that. You just take that concept

00:59:41.740 --> 00:59:45.180
[Guest]: And then you try to interpret it and in a context poem system

00:59:45.980 --> 00:59:49.900
[Guest]: We tend to put a lot more other information on it to try to understand it

00:59:50.460 --> 00:59:54.460
[Guest]: And that tends to cause a very different set of interactions and behavior

00:59:55.020 --> 00:59:57.260
[Guest]: The other aspect is that this stuff is fast

00:59:57.980 --> 01:00:01.100
[Guest]: It's like the worst combinations sometimes of having a book

01:00:01.100 --> 01:00:07.020
[Guest]: And having an argument. A book you can open up and you can always read that page. You can close the book go back and forget it

01:00:07.500 --> 01:00:11.660
[Guest]: A conversation you can have once or twice and then you can say something in anger

01:00:12.220 --> 01:00:14.060
[Guest]: And then leave and everyone will forget it

01:00:14.060 --> 01:00:19.180
[Guest]: But an online conversation you can say something angry and you can put it out there in that moment of anger

01:00:19.580 --> 01:00:23.100
